article.headline: Oregon State 84, Willamette 53
article.story: CORVALLIS, Ore. (AP) -- Angelo Tsagarakis understands he must be confident, or there's no point in taking his shot. "Even if I miss five in a row, there's always a potential I can make the sixth one," he said. The freshman from Affreville, France, certainly didn't lack confidence or the ability to make his shots Friday night when he scored 18 points -- all 3-pointers -- to lead Oregon State to an 84-53 victory over Division III Willamette. "I'm always confident -- even if it doesn't fall," he said. The Beavers (4-2), coming off a triple overtime 87-82 victory over Kansas State last Saturday, strung together back-to-back wins for the first time this season. Chris Stephens scored 19 points for Oregon State, which had final exams this week. David Force led the Bearcats (4-4) with 10 points, and was the only Willamette scorer in double figures. Tsagarakis was 6-for-7 from 3-point range, including a 3-pointer that put the Beavers up 62-37 in the second half. The Bearcats stayed with Oregon State until midway through the first half, when Tsagarakis' 3-pointer put the Beavers ahead 17-12. Oregon State extended its lead with a 13-3 run capped by Stephens' wide-open 3-pointer to take a 32-20 lead. The Beavers led 35-26 at the half. The slow start was nipped when coach Jay John told the team to "pick it up," at the half, Stephens said. "Everybody's tired," he said. "Everybody's had finals this week. Everybody was up late." But despite the rough week -- including the triple overtime victory over Kansas State, the Beavers were simply too fast for the Bearcats to match as the game wore on. Willamette shot just 29 percent from the floor, while the Beavers shot 52 percent. Still, John was impressed with the Bearcats and 17-year coach Gordie James. "They were fighters and they were battlers, no doubt about it," he said. The Bearcats won the last meeting with the Beavers, 64-54, back in 1951. Oregon State was scheduled to get on an early morning flight Saturday for Hawaii, where they'll play the Warriors on Monday.
